I know that it's a privilege to be able to have access to mental health professionals, but please, PLEASE take the time to take care of yourself in any & all ways possible. stress can & will kill you if you don't manage it. you deserve to feel safe & healthy.

this whole experience was so sudden & it made me realize just how badly I need help & need to work out the issues I've been fighting off on my own for so long. you really never know when the breaking point is when your body will not be able to handle the mental stress.
today I finally feel almost fully back to normal. thankfully most of the new medications are temporary & I will likely only end up taking 1 or 2 of the new ones for a more extended time.

we did tests, talked, & *everyone* confirmed that this was 100% just anxiety that irritated my acid reflux & caused other issues. I started last week with 2 medications I regularly take, & this week I'm now on 6 to get all this under control. I'm also looking for a therapist.

including my visit to urgent care & all the primary care appointments I've had, I've seen a medical professional 5 times. it took until a few days after the last appt & talking to my loved ones for my anxiety to finally calm down & realize that I'm okay.

urgent care & my entire body tensed up so hard that I felt like I had done an intense workout after I was done. teeth chattering again, pain everywhere. it was terrifying. I did see a dr this time & by the time I did I realized it was a panic attack.

were at capacity & I had calmed down. the 2nd was early Sunday morning, I suddenly felt heat in my chest that exploded to the rest of my upper body, my heart was RACING & I woke up my bf & told him to call 911 because I thought I was having a heart attack. he drove me to -

I've had many anxiety attacks in my life, but as I've learned this was my 1st time having severe panic attacks. the 1st one was on friday bc I could not breathe & my whole body tensed up & my jaw was chattering so hard - we went to urgent care but didn't see a dr because they -

my anxiety caused me to have a major acid reflux/gerd episode & I had a cough, trouble breathing, chest pain, back pain, major fatigue, muscle spasms, insomnia, heartburn, & 2 MAJOR panic attacks throughout the week.
my baseline anxiety levels were always at maximum & I became a genuine hypochondriac because I convinced myself that I was dying or had some disease every time something was off.

my anxiety has gotten worse & worse over the course of 2021 after my family & I got covid, my cat died, & so many other things piled up & I didn't process that until the 2nd half of the year & even though I've been through worse times in my life, I've never been this anxious.

sorry for the long thread.. but hey friends, reminder that your brain is a powerful thing & you need to take care of yourself. this past week was one of the worst weeks I've had because my anxiety got so bad that I had a meltdown & was physically sick & went to urgent care twice.

sorry for the 4am sadposting I know everyone's tired of me talking about my cat but I just genuinely don't have anywhere else to put my thoughts out into the void.

but still, I just... watching it happen & saying goodbye to an animal you shared like half of your life with is never easy & you just never get the answers. I guess you just never truly get closure. :(

she couldn't walk, she could barely move. she was old & it all happened so fast. she withered away, she stopped even trying, she was just done, so quickly. I know that helping her out of it was the best thing to do & it brought me so much joy to hear that purr one last time.
@thatdamnboulder yes..exactly this 😔 I wish I knew how to turn it off. it's torture

the morning of, I spent a good 2 hours just cuddling her like we used to before & all I wanted was for her to be purring when it was time, & she did purr. it was loud. that last morning was so precious & important to me & I'm glad I got that. she was so tired. she knew.

I just feel...fucking horrible thinking that she may have thought we didn't love her anymore or that I didn't spend enough time with her at the end... I keep wondering over & over & over if she knew how much I loved her 😔

I just keep getting hung up on how miserable she was in the last month, month & a half-ish of her life because her body was failing rapidly & we had to monitor her all the time & keep her in only a few rooms because she couldn't control what came out of her body or when anymore &

there was a short period of time I think in the 2ish months after she died that I was kind of...okay? almost all the time? but for some reason lately I've just gotten so much worse again & it's exhausting & I just cannot seem to accept that she's not here.

once I think "hm I should go pet & kiss my cat" I am absolutely wrecked with the realization every single time that I can't do that anymore. 5 months later. almost every day I have a breakdown over it.

constantly in front of me & I hate it. I think in grieving gracie that has happened to me a lot...my brain is just used to her being home & expecting to see her at home that when I'm not there or when I'm just sorta going about my routine I don't notice that she isn't there, but

when I remember I'm like "oh shit I need to reach out, I love this person & I don't want them to think I've forgotten them" because it's true I love the people I love with so much of myself, oh my god, but my brain just doesn't process the existence of things & people unless it's

it stunts the healing process & I never made that connection before & it's so true. for me, at least. because I have pretty bad object permanence especially with people, in the least awful way possible if I don't interact daily with you I just kind of forget you in a way. like..

I saw someone bring up how when you have object permanence issues with adhd/nd stuff it affects people too... & they made the further point that it often makes grief harder because we sort of just. forget that someone is gone. & when we remember the grief comes all over again.

& with all that being said, while I don't think I will ever leave social media nor will I ever stop making & sharing content (& would actually love to do more!) I think I am going to actively try to distance certain aspects of it from myself & just do better, for my own health

tldr; social media can be beautiful. it brings people together, it creates communities & safe spaces, it spreads news like wildfire, it can educate. but there has always been & will ALWAYS be an extremely dark side to it & you NEED to be careful, especially when you're young.

anyways sorry for the long rant - but this has been on my mind a LOT lately & I think it's important to realize & talk about this stuff. I know I need to re-evaluate my relationship with social media & learn how to separate myself more from it, I think many of us do!!

learn to balance social media with real life while you're still young (I know I'm young, too, but I'm well into adulthood & the damage has been done). you don't want to spend all your 20s & maybe 30s trying to unpack these feelings that are already deeply ingrained into your life

I'm 24 & the fact that I base a good bit of my self worth off interactions online & the fact that thousands of people are able to see me & judge me & I have gotten literal panic attacks & have been sent into derealization episodes due to notifications or discourse is not normal

to all the kids/teens who might see this: I am telling you, when adults tell you to be cautious about social media, when we tell you to avoid certain things & people or to stop sharing certain things online, PLEASE LISTEN TO US. we were EXACTLY the same & it fucked us up.

looking to my past I genuinely think that when you get to high school is probably the earliest okay age to start social media. that even might be too early honestly but I really don't think kids younger than that should be on it, besides maybe just to talk to friends.

there are so many things I have done, said, experienced, seen, & been through between the ages of like... 8 to 20, that I should not have experienced, in part due to many factors of course but in LARGE part I think due to what I believed was normal because of social media

& your experience online does not stop online, even if you think it stays there - it doesn't. the things you read & see other people doing stays in your head & it normalizes (especially from tumblr!!!) shit that should NOT be normalized.

when you pair all the things you see & do online with the naivety of being a kid, then teenager going through puberty who is online 24/7.... that REALLY messes you up with the added factor of everything else going on in your life during SUCH formative years

the "content creator" thing with cosplay at the age of... god, idk 15 or something? & there have been very few days that have passed since I was a kid that I haven't posted online in some way & you may think that it's mostly harmless but as years pass you realize it DOES

I unfortunately feel like I am very much a prime example of the "kid who grew up on the internet" trope, starting with online games & facebook in elementary school that progressed to tumblr in middle/high school & continued onto every other platform & getting into -

social media can be a wonderful tool for communication, education, entertainment, creativity, & building relationships & communities, but there is absolutely no doubt that it has HUGE negative impacts on both individual & societal levels

I don't even know where I'd be if not for all the amazing things that have come into my life from it, but it is REALLY difficult to reframe your relationship with social media & distance yourself from the negatives when you've been chronically online since you were like...5

at the end of the day I am really thankful for all the connections I've made with people, the experiences I've had, & things I've learned because of social media but, there are times where I wish I never got into it or at least not to the degree that I did or as early as I did
